  "parent": "no",
  "notes": "Norwegian Bokmål — majority written standard (~85%), Urban East Norwegian phonology (Kristoffersen 2000). QUANTITY: as in Swedish, a stressed vowel is long before a single consonant and short before a geminate or a cluster; doubled letters are grapheme keys mapping to /Cː/, clusters map to the concatenated phonemes, and allophone rules shorten the stressed nucleus before them. VOWELS: short ⟨a⟩ is [a], long is [ɑː]; unstressed ⟨e⟩ is [ə] (the ubiquitous ending vowel). RETROFLEXION: ⟨rt rd rn rs rl⟩ → [ʈ ɖ ɳ ʂ ɭ]. SOFTENING: ⟨k g sk⟩ → [ç j ʃ] before a front vowel. SILENT D: word-final ⟨nd⟩→[n], ⟨ld⟩→[l]; ⟨hv⟩→[v]. R: the phoneme is the apical /r/ (Kristoffersen); the tap [ɾ] is one realisation. TONEMES (accent 1/2) are suprasegmental and are NOT encoded; the gold marks them (¹/²), a convention difference rather than an error.",
  "quality": "research",
